# [MAPRG](../wg/maprg.html)

**Session:** Measurement and Analysis for Protocols Research Group (MAPRG)  
**Date:** IETF 125  
**Chairs:** Dave Plonka, Mirja Kühlewind  

## Summary
The MAPRG session at IETF 125 featured a robust agenda focused on bridging the gap between academic research and IETF protocol work. The session included several invited talks from the Internet Measurement Conference (IMC) 2024 and 2025, as well as previews of unpublished work regarding IPv6 and VPNs. Key themes included DNS resolver vulnerabilities, RPKI adoption and Route Origin Validation (ROV) measurement, IPv6 de-preference in VPN environments, email delivery path centralization, internationalized X.509 certificate compliance, and vulnerabilities in the NTP ecosystem.

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Intro and Administrivia
**Speakers:** Dave Plonka, Mirja Kühlewind
**Slide Title:** [Intro Mirja/Dave](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-intro-mirjadave-01)
The chairs introduced the session as a forum for ambassadors between the IRTF/IETF and the academic community. The group’s focus is on research rather than standards creation.

### 2. Measurement of Systemic DNS Resolver Vulnerabilities
**Speaker:** Yuxi Chen
**Slide Title:** [Heads-up Talk: Measurement of Systemic DNS Resolver Vulnerabilities (Informing Six DNSOP I-Ds)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-heads-up-talk-measurement-of-systemic-dns-resolver-vulnerabilities-informing-six-dnsop-i-ds-01)
*   **Discussion:** The speaker detailed how subtle gaps in DNS specifications lead to systemic vulnerabilities across major vendors. Two major attacks were highlighted: **DNSBomb** (pulsing DoS via timeout aggregation) and **NRBeste** (cache poisoning via ECS prefix exploitation).
*   **Protocol Impact:** The research informs six Internet-Drafts in the `dnsop` working group covering cache delegation, query handling, and packet preprocessing.
*   **Feedback:** Yuxi Chen encouraged the community to review the drafts on the datatracker and provide feedback on technical approach and structure.

### 3. RPKI and ROA Adoption
**Speaker:** Deepak
**Slide Title:** [Are you RPKI Ready: The Road Left to Full ROA Adoption](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-are-you-rpki-ready-the-road-left-to-full-roa-adoption-01)
*   **Discussion:** While over 50% of routed prefixes are covered by ROAs, the remaining 50% face complex technical and non-technical barriers. Challenges include identifying the correct issuing organization, managing sub-prefixes with different origins, and inter-organizational communication.
*   **Platform:** The researchers introduced the "Are You RPKI Ready" dashboard to help operators plan ROAs.
*   **Findings:** 50% of the remaining prefixes have low technical barriers but are managed by organizations that have not yet issued ROAs. 20% (largely ARIN/DoD) face significant policy barriers.

### 4. Global ROV Deployments and Dependencies
**Speaker:** Wei Tong
**Slide Title:** [RScope: Unveiling Global ROV Deployments and Dependencies in the Post-ROV Era](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-rscope-unveiling-global-rov-deployments-and-dependencies-in-the-post-rov-era-00)
*   **Discussion:** Measuring ROV (Route Origin Validation) is increasingly difficult as more ASes deploy filtering. The **RScope** framework uses a "divide and conquer" approach by giving specific ROAs to specific Relying Parties (RPs) to identify which ASes rely on which infrastructure.
*   **Findings:** Many ASes rely on a single RP (contrary to RFC recommendations). Higher-ranked ASes typically deploy their own RPs, while lower-ranked ones benefit from upstream filtering.
*   **Q&A:** Deepak asked about the noise introduced by networks using multiple RPs. Wei Tong noted that RScope tests combinations and found that some ASes require consistency across multiple RPs before filtering.

### 5. IPv6 De-preference in VPNs
**Speaker:** Yejin Cho
**Slide Title:** [What IPv6 RFCs Don’t Say About VPNs](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-what-ipv6-rfcs-dont-say-about-vpns-02)
*   **Discussion:** VPN users often experience "IPv6 de-preference" where IPv4 is chosen over IPv6 despite Happy Eyeballs. This is primarily because VPNs often assign Unique Local Addresses (ULAs). According to **RFC 6724**, IPv4 public/private addresses are preferred over IPv6 ULAs.
*   **Proposed Solutions:** Assigning unique GUAs, shared static GUAs, creating a new "Tunnel Local Address" (TLA) class, or changing prioritization rules.
*   **Community Feedback:** 
    *   **Lorenzo Colitti** argued for maintaining end-to-end connectivity (GUA allocation) and suggested providing a /64 to clients.
    *   **Suresh Krishnan** recommended taking this work to the `6man` working group, as creating new address classes or changing address selection rules requires protocol action.

### 6. Intermediate Paths of Email Delivery
**Speaker:** Shibo Cui
**Slide Title:** [Understanding and Characterizing Intermediate Paths of Email Delivery](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-understanding-and-characterizing-intermediate-paths-of-email-delivery-01)
*   **Discussion:** Traditional end-to-end email models have shifted toward hosting-based models with multiple intermediate nodes (security providers, signature providers).
*   **Findings:** Significant centralization was observed, with Microsoft (Outlook) participating in roughly 70% of intermediate paths. Regional dependencies were noted; for example, South American email paths are highly dependent on North American infrastructure.
*   **Impact:** Mirja Kühlewind noted that the talk had already spurred discussion on email-related mailing lists.

### 7. Internationalized X.509 Certificates (Unicerts)
**Speaker:** Mingming Zhang
**Slide Title:** [Analyzing Compliance and Complications of Integrating Internationalized X.509 Certificates](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-analyzing-compliance-and-complications-of-integrating-internationalized-x509-certificates-01)
*   **Discussion:** The speaker analyzed "Unicerts" containing non-ASCII characters. Using **RFC-GPT** to navigate complex standards, the researchers identified 250,000 non-compliant certificates in Certificate Transparency (CT) logs.
*   **Vulnerabilities:** Inconsistencies in how TLS libraries parse malformed IDNs or handle bidirectional characters can lead to common name forgery or misleading browser warning pages.
*   **Q&A:** In response to Mirja Kühlewind, Mingming Zhang noted they have disclosed issues to Let's Encrypt and other CAs. Lieven (ETH Zurich) asked about real-world exploits; the speaker clarified that while inconsistencies were verified in CT monitors, no real-world exploits have been observed yet.

### 8. NTP Ecosystem Vulnerabilities
**Speaker:** Jinchen Huang
**Slide Title:** [Measuring the Time Source Vulnerabilities in the NTP Ecosystem](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-maprg-measuring-the-time-source-vulnerabilities-in-the-ntp-ecosystem-05)
*   **Discussion:** A large-scale scan revealed that 1.1 million open NTP servers are "bad timekeepers" (offset >10s). Vulnerabilities include "single source" dependency and "dangling IPs" where NTP servers point to stale cloud IP addresses that attackers can take over.
*   **Proposed Solution:** **NTS-MON**, a monitoring and ranking system to provide clients with a list of accurate and available NTS-supported servers.
*   **Feedback:** **Karen O'Donoghue** (NTP WG Chair) invited the speaker to present to the NTP working group and noted that the NTP pool is actively working on NTS support.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Email Research:** Participants are encouraged to follow the ongoing discussions on email-related mailing lists regarding intermediate path centralization.
*   **VPN IPv6:** Authors of the VPN IPv6 study were directed to bring their proposals regarding address selection and ULAs to the **6man** working group for formal protocol consideration.
*   **NTP Security:** Jinchen Huang to follow up with Karen O'Donoghue regarding a presentation at the NTP working group.

## Next Steps
*   MAPRG will likely meet at IETF 126 in Vienna.
